body of mass 5 kg is thrown vertically upward with a velocity of 10 m/s. What is the maximum height reached?","questions.0.options.0.image":"","questions.0.options.0.text":"5 m","questions.0.options.0._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd6c","questions.0.options.1.image":"","questions.0.options.1.text":"10 m","questions.0.options.1._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd6d","questions.0.options.2.image":"","questions.0.options.2.text":"15 m","questions.0.options.2._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd6e","questions.0.options.3.image":"","questions.0.options.3.text":"20 m","questions.0.options.3._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd6f","questions.0.correctOption":0,"questions.0.explanation":"Using v² = u² - 2gh, at max height v=0, so h = u²/2g = 100/20 = 5m","questions.0.marks":2,"questions.0.negativeMarks":0.5,"questions.0._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd6b","questions.1.sourceQuestionId":null,"questions.1.subject":null,"questions.1.course":null,"questions.1.questionImage":"","questions.1.difficulty":"","questions.1.displayOrder":0,"questions.1.questionText":"The SI unit of electric current is:","questions.1.options.0.image":"","questions.1.options.0.text":"Volt","questions.1.options.0._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd71","questions.1.options.1.image":"","questions.1.options.1.text":"Ohm","questions.1.options.1._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd72","questions.1.options.2.image":"","questions.1.options.2.text":"Ampere","questions.1.options.2._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd73","questions.1.options.3.image":"","questions.1.options.3.text":"Watt","questions.1.options.3._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd74","questions.1.correctOption":2,"questions.1.explanation":"Ampere (A) is the SI unit of electric current.","questions.1.marks":1,"questions.1.negativeMarks":0,"questions.1._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd70","questions.2.sourceQuestionId":null,"questions.2.subject":null,"questions.2.course":null,"questions.2.questionImage":"","questions.2.difficulty":"","questions.2.displayOrder":0,"questions.2.questionText":"What is the derivative of sin(x)?","questions.2.options.0.image":"","questions.2.options.0.text":"-cos(x)","questions.2.options.0._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd76","questions.2.options.1.image":"","questions.2.options.1.text":"cos(x)","questions.2.options.1._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd77","questions.2.options.2.image":"","questions.2.options.2.text":"tan(x)","questions.2.options.2._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd78","questions.2.options.3.image":"","questions.2.options.3.text":"-sin(x)","questions.2.options.3._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd79","questions.2.correctOption":1,"questions.2.explanation":"The derivative of sin(x) with respect to x is cos(x).","questions.2.marks":1,"questions.2.negativeMarks":0,"questions.2._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd75","questions.3.sourceQuestionId":null,"questions.3.subject":null,"questions.3.course":null,"questions.3.questionImage":"","questions.3.difficulty":"","questions.3.displayOrder":0,"questions.3.questionText":"Which of the following is the chemical formula for water?","questions.3.options.0.image":"","questions.3.options.0.text":"CO2","questions.3.options.0._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd7b","questions.3.options.1.image":"","questions.3.options.1.text":"H2O","questions.3.options.1._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd7c","questions.3.options.2.image":"","questions.3.options.2.text":"NaCl","questions.3.options.2._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd7d","questions.3.options.3.image":"","questions.3.options.3.text":"O2","questions.3.options.3._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd7e","questions.3.correctOption":1,"questions.3.explanation":"Water has the chemical formula H2O (two hydrogen atoms and one oxygen atom).","questions.3.marks":1,"questions.3.negativeMarks":0,"questions.3._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd7a","questions.4.sourceQuestionId":null,"questions.4.subject":null,"questions.4.course":null,"questions.4.questionImage":"","questions.4.difficulty":"","questions.4.displayOrder":0,"questions.4.questionText":"In a right triangle, if one angle is 90° and another is 30°, what is the third angle?","questions.4.options.0.image":"","questions.4.options.0.text":"30°","questions.4.options.0._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd80","questions.4.options.1.image":"","questions.4.options.1.text":"45°","questions.4.options.1._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd81","questions.4.options.2.image":"","questions.4.options.2.text":"60°","questions.4.options.2._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd82","questions.4.options.3.image":"","questions.4.options.3.text":"90°","questions.4.options.3._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd83","questions.4.correctOption":2,"questions.4.explanation":"Sum of angles in a triangle = 180°. So third angle = 180 - 90 - 30 = 60°.","questions.4.marks":1,"questions.4.negativeMarks":0,"questions.4._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd7f","questions.5.sourceQuestionId":null,"questions.5.subject":null,"questions.5.course":null,"questions.5.questionImage":"","questions.5.difficulty":"","questions.5.displayOrder":0,"questions.5.questionText":"What is the value of acceleration due to gravity on the surface of the Earth?","questions.5.options.0.image":"","questions.5.options.0.text":"8.9 m/s²","questions.5.options.0._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd85","questions.5.options.1.image":"","questions.5.options.1.text":"9.8 m/s²","questions.5.options.1._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd86","questions.5.options.2.image":"","questions.5.options.2.text":"10.8 m/s²","questions.5.options.2._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd87","questions.5.options.3.image":"","questions.5.options.3.text":"11.2 m/s²","questions.5.options.3._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd88","questions.5.correctOption":1,"questions.5.explanation":"The standard value of acceleration due to gravity on Earth's surface is approximately 9.8 m/s².","questions.5.marks":1,"questions.5.negativeMarks":0,"questions.5._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd84","questions.6.sourceQuestionId":null,"questions.6.subject":null,"questions.6.course":null,"questions.6.questionImage":"","questions.6.difficulty":"","questions.6.displayOrder":0,"questions.6.questionText":"Which element has the atomic number 6?","questions.6.options.0.image":"","questions.6.options.0.text":"Nitrogen","questions.6.options.0._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd8a","questions.6.options.1.image":"","questions.6.options.1.text":"Oxygen","questions.6.options.1._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd8b","questions.6.options.2.image":"","questions.6.options.2.text":"Carbon","questions.6.options.2._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd8c","questions.6.options.3.image":"","questions.6.options.3.text":"Boron","questions.6.options.3._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd8d","questions.6.correctOption":2,"questions.6.explanation":"Carbon has atomic number 6.","questions.6.marks":1,"questions.6.negativeMarks":0,"questions.6._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd89","questions.7.sourceQuestionId":null,"questions.7.subject":null,"questions.7.course":null,"questions.7.questionImage":"","questions.7.difficulty":"","questions.7.displayOrder":0,"questions.7.questionText":"What is the integral of 2x dx?","questions.7.options.0.image":"","questions.7.options.0.text":"x + C","questions.7.options.0._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd8f","questions.7.options.1.image":"","questions.7.options.1.text":"x² + C","questions.7.options.1._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd90","questions.7.options.2.image":"","questions.7.options.2.text":"2x² + C","questions.7.options.2._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd91","questions.7.options.3.image":"","questions.7.options.3.text":"x³ + C","questions.7.options.3._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd92","questions.7.correctOption":1,"questions.7.explanation":"∫2x dx = 2(x²/2) + C = x² + C","questions.7.marks":2,"questions.7.negativeMarks":0.5,"questions.7._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd8e","questions.8.sourceQuestionId":null,"questions.8.subject":null,"questions.8.course":null,"questions.8.questionImage":"","questions.8.difficulty":"","questions.8.displayOrder":0,"questions.8.questionText":"Ohm's law states that:","questions.8.options.0.image":"","questions.8.options.0.text":"V = IR","questions.8.options.0._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd94","questions.8.options.1.image":"","questions.8.options.1.text":"V = I/R","questions.8.options.1._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd95","questions.8.options.2.image":"","questions.8.options.2.text":"V = R/I","questions.8.options.2._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd96","questions.8.options.3.image":"","questions.8.options.3.text":"I = VR","questions.8.options.3._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd97","questions.8.correctOption":0,"questions.8.explanation":"Ohm's law states V = IR, where V is voltage, I is current, and R is resistance.","questions.8.marks":1,"questions.8.negativeMarks":0,"questions.8._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd93","questions.9.sourceQuestionId":null,"questions.9.subject":null,"questions.9.course":null,"questions.9.questionImage":"","questions.9.difficulty":"","questions.9.displayOrder":0,"questions.9.questionText":"The passive voice of 'She writes a letter' is:","questions.9.options.0.image":"","questions.9.options.0.text":"A letter is written by her.","questions.9.options.0._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd99","questions.9.options.1.image":"","questions.9.options.1.text":"A letter was written by her.","questions.9.options.1._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd9a","questions.9.options.2.image":"","questions.9.options.2.text":"A letter has been written by her.","questions.9.options.2._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd9b","questions.9.options.3.image":"","questions.9.options.3.text":"A letter will be written by her.","questions.9.options.3._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd9c","questions.9.correctOption":0,"questions.9.explanation":"Present simple active → Present simple passive: 'is + past participle'.","questions.9.marks":1,"questions.9.negativeMarks":0,"questions.9._id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd98","isActive":true,"createdAt":"2026-03-05T04:53:02.588Z","updatedAt":"2026-03-05T04:53:18.251Z","__v":0},"populated":{},"baseError":null,"errors":{},"id":"69a90c2e06be35c7e6b0fd6a","title":"IOE MOCK TEST - I","recordActions":[{"name":"show","actionType":"record","icon":"Monitor","label":"show","resourceId":"MockTes